Case Study Seven¶

Minimum Financial Loss Prediction¶

David Grijalva, Nicole Norelli, & Mingyang Nick YU¶

12/03/2021¶

Abstract
The following deliverable focuses on building a predictive model with the goal of reducing a company's monetary loss due to incorrect predictions. In this case study, the team trained and explored 6 different predictive models to achieve the company's goal.

1. Introduction¶

This case study focused on correctly predicting each target class in order to prevent monetary losses. For each wrong classification of class 1, there is a monetary loss of 100 dollars. For each wrong classification of class 0, there is a monetary loss of 25 dollars. The goal of this case study is to reduce the overall financial loss produced by the model.

Logistic Regression¶

Logistic Regression is a linear classification model which outputs the probability of the target variable. In its core, it works similarly to a linear regresssion with the difference that it uses the sigmoid function to convert the target variable between zero and one. Similar to Multiple Linear Regression, Logistic Regression can utilize both categorical variables and numeric variables as predictors. For binary classification problems, Logistic Regression takes a two-part loss function. When the target 𝑦 is 1 loss is: −𝑦log(𝑝) , when the target is 0 loss is: (1−𝑦)log(1−𝑝) .

Sigmoid Function

$$ s= {\frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}} $$

Ridge Regularization (L2)

Ridge regularization, or L2, is utilized as a penalty term for Logistic Regression in Scikit-learn by default. The penalty for this is the squared coefficients multiplied by Lambda, which controls the strength of the penalty. Unlike L1 regularization, L2 does not provide feature selection. All features are penalized uniformly but will never reach zero. In general, L2 is the primary regularization method used to prevent overfitting the model.

Penalty Term
$\lambda \sum\limits_{j=0}^k m_j ^2 $
Where $\lambda $ is the strength of the penalty. If $\lambda=0 $ then there would be no penalty applied and the original coefficient would be returned.


RandomForest¶

A Random Forest is an ensemble statistical learning method composed of several decision trees (known as weak learners) for which each individual prediction is combined to make a final overall prediction. Random Forest uses the concept of bootstrap aggregation, also called bagging. In simple terms, bootstrap is a sampling method with replacement (it can select the same instance on multiple samples), meaning, it randomly samples a subset of the training dataset population. When an algorithm uses bagging, it simply means training a weak learner (Decision Tree) for each of the subsamples selected. Different from bagging, Random Forest randomly subsamples parameters to be considered at each split. This produces a forest of weak learners that are less correlated from one another, and usually generates better prediction results compared to predictions using bagging alone.

To understand how Random Forest works it is important to understand how Decision Trees work. Decisions Trees are a supervised method that can be used for regression or classification. The key concept is that for every feature available, the Decision Tree splits the data into two branches, and for each split, it measures its information gain. The algorithm recursively repeats this operation until the stopping criteria is met.

There are two main methods to measure information gain: Gini and Entropy.

Gini Impurity¶

Gini Impurity is a measurement of the probability of incorrect classification for a new data point. The lower the Gini impurity is the more information is gained.

$$ G = \sum \limits _{i=1} ^{C} P(i) \dot (1-P(i)) $$

Entropy¶

Entropy is a mathematical formula to measure randomness. The lower the Entropy is the more information is gained due to having less randomness.

$$ H(X) = -\sum \limits _{i=1} ^{n} P(x_{i}) log_{b} P(x_{i}) $$


XGBoost¶

XGBoost is a popular algorithm created by Tianqi Chen and released in 2016. This algorithm can be found on many production applications used by major companies. There are three key aspects that make XGBoost an effective learner:
1) The use of boosting
2) The use of gradients.
3) L2 regularization

Similar to Random Forest, boosting is also an ensemble method that uses weak learners to generate a strong one. Unlike Random Forest, which generates multiple and uncorrelated weak learners, boosting is composed of rounds or iterations of weak learners. The unique part of boosting is that each round tries to improve on the previous prediction, and each iteration is sequential to previous iterations rather than in parallel (Random Forest). Each of the iterations learns from its previous errors by using the gradient of the loss function. Specifically, after the first iteration the weak learners are no longer optimizing for the dependent variable, but rather for the residuals. These weak learner iterations continue until the stopping criteria is met.

To account for the prediction errors, XGBoost uses an approximate loss function which can be used with first and second-order partial derivatives.

$$ J= \sum \limits _{i}l(p _{i}, y_{i}) + \sum \limits _{k} \Omega (f _{k}) $$

This first equation displays a general loss function calculating the residuals or difference between the dependent variable and the prediction.

$$ \Omega (f) = \gamma T + \frac{1}{2} \lambda \rvert\lvert w \rvert\rvert^2 $$

The second equation displays the penalty imposed to reduce complexity in the terminal leaves.

Another key feature of XGBoost is that it has L2 regularization by default. The penalty imposed by the L2 is the squared coefficients multiplied by Lambda, which controls the strength of the penalty. Unlike L1 regularization, L2 does not provide feature selection. All features are penalized uniformly but will never reach zero. In general, L2 is the primary regularization method used to prevent overfitting the model.

$$ \lambda \sum\limits_{j=0}^k m_j ^2 $$


Where $\lambda $ is the strength of the penalty. If $\lambda=0 $ then there would be no penalty applied.


Neural Network¶

Neural Networks are supervised machine learning models composed of multiple layers. The inspiration for neural networks came from the basic understanding of how a human brain works. A brain is composed of neurons, which receive signals from multiple sources. Once the combined signals meet a certain threshold, the neuron fires an electrical impulse, which is transmitted to the subsequent neurons to which it is connected.

In a neural network, perceptrons (or neurons) are designed to perform this function. Neural networks are comprised of multiple layers of neurons. The layers between the input and the output are called hidden layers. A number of neurons for each layer in the network is designated. In the first hidden layer, each neuron receives all of the input variables and calculates a regression with different weights ($w$) assigned to each variable ($x$). A bias term ($b$) is added, and the result of the regression equation is passed through an activation function (${\sigma}$).

$z = {\sigma}(w_i x_i + b)$

The activation function is chosen by the user, but is typically nonlinear, such as a sigmoid or Rectified Linear Unit (ReLU). This function performs the threshold activation one would see in a biological cell and adds nonlinearity to the model. The initial values for weights and bias terms are randomly assigned from a distribution which can be specified.

The outputs from the first hidden layer are then passed as inputs to the next hidden layer, and the process repeats. In a dense neural network, all the neurons in each layer are connected to all the neurons in the previous and subsequent layers. The final output layer matches the target, with one output for a regression target, one or two outputs for a binary classification, or the appropriate number of outputs for a multi-class classification.

A neural network is "trained" using an optimizer and a loss function. An appropriate loss function is chosen, depending on the type of problem. Typical loss functions include "BinaryCrossentropy", "SparseCategoricalCrossentropy", and "MeanSquaredError." An optimizer is also selected. Historically, stochastic gradient descent was often used as the default optimizer, but it is currently a slower choice. More modern optimizers include "adam" and "RMSprop." The loss is calculated, and the optimizer updates the weights of the neural network accordingly during the "backwards pass." This is the time-consuming portion of the training, with forward passes being relatively quick to provide predictions.

Because neural networks are typically used with large data sets, data is broken down into batches. Batch size (the number of points in the network at one time) is specified, as well as the number of epochs (number of passes through the entire data set). Early stopping criteria can also be established. This monitors the loss, and a "patience" threshold is set. If the loss value increases for more successive epochs than the specified patience value, early stopping is reached. The early stopping criteria helps to avoid overfitting the data.

An additional method to prevent overfitting and provide regularization to neural networks is the use of drop-out layers (Tensorflow documentation). Using this method, a certain proportion of inputs are randomly set to zero at each specified step, and the inputs that were not set to zero are scaled up by 1/(1-rate) so the sum of all inputs stays the same.

Ensemble¶

An Ensemble model is a machine learning technique that combines the out of fold predictions of several well tuned base models and feeds them as predictors to the next level(s) model which provides the final prediction.

The architecture of this ensemble model consists of two levels or more. For the purpose of introduction, a two level structured is used. Level-1 (well tuned base models) can contain two or more predictive models. Each model will be used to calculate out of fold predictions for each data point on the training data. The models themselves are also fitted based on training data. These models can use any statistical method as long as each is consistent with either the classification or regression task. For this case study, Logistic Regression, Random Forrest, and XGBoost were chosen (each described in the sections above). Level-2 consists of a single model which takes input features of a combined array of all the level-1 model out of fold predictions and provides final prediction results. For this case study, the level-2 model of choice was a Logistic Regression. For classification tasks, out of fold prediction probability is preferred rather than direct results, as it allows the level-2 model to learn more details of out of fold predictions through level-1 models. To generate new predictions for the test data, it will first flow through level-1 models to generate prediction probabilities together in the same order as the training data, and then feed those probabilities through the trained level-2 to get test predictions.

2. Methods¶

EDA and Cleaning¶

There were 160,000 instances and 51 features (including the target variable) provided for this anonymous dataset. Initial inspection identified that feature "x37" required conversion from a categorical variable into a numerical variable. The function remove_pattern_convert_float helped achieve this by removing the dollar sign in front of the string and changing it into float64, which is the ideal data type for this variable. All features had a small percentage of missing data, and most of the missing data was between 0.01% and 0.02%.

A few variables had extremely high correlations with each other (>0.999). In order to solve some of the missing data issues as well as very high correlations between a few variables at the same time, the variables were first ordered in ascending order based on percentage of missing data. Then an algorithm to delete the variables with correlations greater than 0.999 was deployed. This eliminated attributes with extremely high correlations (>0.999) with the retained attribute having less missing data than the deleted attribute. Specifically, this algorithm eliminated features 'x6' and 'x41'. Exploratory data analysis indicated most of the numeric variables were normally distributed. Thus, using a mean strategy to impute numeric variables and a most_frequent strategy for categorical variables was appropriate for the remaining attributes.

Data Split, Pipeline and Helper Functions¶

In order to evaluate model performance more objectively, the entire data set was stratified split into an 80/20 train/test set. A random state was set to ensure reproducibility. Individual pipelines were created for categorical variables and numeric variables. This is due to different imputation and treatment requirements for these two categories. For categorical_pipe (categorical variable pipeline), the data was first imputed by SimpleImputer using the 'most_frequent' strategy, and then one hot encoded with unknown levels ignored during training. For numeric_pipe (numerical variable pipeline), the data was also imputed using SimpleImputer, but using the 'mean' strategy instead, and then scaled by MinMaxScaller into a range of 0-1. Both of the pipelines were transformed by ColumnTransformer during runtime as a pre-processing step for the further modeling pipeline.

As has been instructed by the company, every incorrectly classified instance 1 will mean a loss of 100 dollars, and every incorrectly classified instance 0 will mean a loss of 25 dollars. A few helper functions were created specifically for targeting the tasks given. estimate_total_loss function was used to calculate normalized total financial loss based on misclassification on the test data. This function takes in true labels as 'y_test' and predicted labels as 'pred'. It then calculates total loss with all test data given, specifically the total number of incorrectly predicted for class 1 is multiplied by 100 and total number of incorrectly predicted for class 0 is multiplied by 25. This total loss is then normalized based on the total number of instances in the test set. The resulting calculation is the normalized loss on the given amount of test data. In order words, the result is the average loss per instance of the test data. This means the smaller the average loss the better, and the objective was to find the best algorithm or best cut off for prediction probability that would minimize the average loss.

The find_best_prob function was used to find a suitable cut-off and lowest dollar loss with a given model or prediction probability of class 1 (with 1.0 indicating absolute confidence the prediction is class 1 and 0.0 is absolute confidence the prediction is class 0). The function scanned through class 1 prediction probability from 0.50 to 1.0 with increments of 0.005. It utilized the above estimate_total_loss function to find a cut off that provided the lowest average dollar loss and returned a tuple of the best cut off and lowest dollar loss. The reason for only scanning from 0.5 was because incorrect predictions of class 1 had higher finacial penalties, thus only the probability that would generate more confidence for class 1 needed to be explored. This function also handled neural network model prediction from Keras and direct probability prediction of both classes (with specific parameters set to True for individual scenarios).

The plot_roc_curve_custom was used to plot the receiver operating characteristic curve. get_confusion_matrix was used to print the confusion matrix on predictions for the given test set. get_classification_report was used to get a comprehensive classification report including Training accuracy, Test Accuracy, classification report on test set, and it reused plot_roc_curve_custom and get_confusion_matrix functions as part of the comprehensive report as well. cv_common and cv_summary were used to present GridSearchCV or RandomSearchCV results to view hyperparameter combinations in a straightforward manner. plot_early_stop_rounds was designed for plotting Neural Network Train/Test Loss vs. Epochs.

Logistic Regression - Model 1¶

Logistic Regression was utilized as a baseline model. A pipeline incorporating both the preprocessing pipeline and the LogisticRegression was created under the variable pipeline_lr_m1. GridSearchCV was utilized to test all parameter combinations in the grid, and StratifiedKFold was utilized for 10-fold cross validation to lower any issue with class imbalance. roc_auc (area under the curve) was utilized as the scoring metric to evaluate both classes more fairly during search and extract the best parameter set because area under the curve considers both the False Positive Rate of one class and the True Positive Rate of the other class. A bigger AUC value also correlates with lower average financial loss after tuning prediction probability. class_weight was adjusted to "balanced" to automatically adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies to help adjust target class imbalance. random_state was set for reproducibility and max_iter was set to 10,000 to allow the Logistic Regression algorithm to take more steps towards convergence. Other parameters tuned by GridSearchCV are displayed under the variable params_lr:

Logistic Regression with interaction terms - Model 2¶

Logistic Regression was utilized as a primary model. A pipeline incorporating the preprocessing pipeline; the interactions pipeline, which utilized PolynomialFeatures supplied by SKLearn to create interaction terms for all existing features; the features were scaled by MinMaxScaler to 0-1 range; and the model pipeline LogisticRegression was created under the variable pipeline_lr_m3. GridSearchCV was utilized to test all parameter combinations in the grid, and StratifiedKFold was utilized for 10-fold cross validation to lower any issue with class imbalance. roc_auc (area under the curve) was utilized as the scoring metric to evaluate both classes more fairly during search and extract the best parameter set because area under the curve considers both the False Positive Rate of one class and the True Positive Rate of the other class. A bigger AUC value also correlates with lower average financial loss after tuning prediction probability. class_weight was adjusted to "balanced" to automatically adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies to help adjust target class imbalance. random_state was set for reproducibility and max_iter was set to 10,000 to allow the Logistic Regression algorithm to take more steps towards convergence. Other parameters tuned by GridSearchCV were the same as those in Model 1.

This particular model took an extremely long time to train with intensive memory and CPU requirements. On the machine it was trained, it took around 5 days 10 hours and 39 minutes. The best parameter combination found was for C=10, using 'liblinear' solver. After the best hyperparameters were found, the find_best_prob was deployed to find the best cut off and average monetary loss. Details will be presented under Results section.

Random Forest - Model 3¶

Random Forest was utilized as a baseline model. A pipeline incorporating both the preprocessing pipeline and the RandomForestClassifier was created under the variable rf_pipeline. RandomizedSearchCV was utilized due to the many different parameter combinations for tuning. Ten sets of different parameters were sampled from the defined grid without replacement, and StratifiedKFold was utilized for 10-fold cross validation due to the slight target class imbalance. roc_auc (area under the curve) was utilized as the scoring metric to evaluate both classes more fairly during search and extract the best parameter set because area under the curve considers both the False Positive Rate of one class and the True Positive Rate of the other class. A bigger AUC value also correlates with lower average financial loss after tuning prediction probability. max_features was set to "auto," which utilized the square root of the number of features. This has empirically generated good results for the Random Forest Classifier. class_weight was adjusted to "balanced" to automatically adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies to help adjust target class imbalance. Random state was set for reproducibility. Other parameters sampled by RandomizedSearchCV are displayed under the variable params_rf:

XGBoost - Model 4¶

A pipeline incorporating both the preprocessing pipeline and the XGBClassifier (XGBoost Scikit-learn wrapper) was created under the variable xgb_pipeline to be used for the search. RandomizedSearchCV was utilized due to the many different parameter combinations needed for tuning. Ten sets of different parameters were sampled from the defined grid without replacement, and StratifiedKFold was utilized for 10-fold cross validation due to the heavy target class imbalance. roc_auc (area under the curve) was utilized as the scoring metric to evaluate both classes more fairly during the search to extract the best parameter set because area under the curve considers both the False Positive Rate of one class and the True Positive Rate of the other class. A bigger AUC value also correlates with lower average financial loss after tuning prediction probability. The objective function for XGBoost was set to "binary:logistic" because probability was needed to calculate the scoring of roc_auc. n_estimators for the XGBClassifier was set to 800. This value has been discovered through trials and errors, and it is purposely set slightly on the higher side to push the model performance further. The final parameters sampled by RandomizedSearchCV are displayed under the variable search_space:

After the best hyperparameters were found, the find_best_prob was deployed to find the best cut off and average monetary loss. Details will be presented under Results section.

Neural Network - Model 5¶

The training and test data were first fit and transformed using the preprocessing pipeline. Sequential Deep Neural Network was created using Tensorflow and Keras. The Input Layer had 76 input variables after preprocessing transformation. Then it proceeded to a dense layer with 250 neurons followed by a dropout layer with 20% of neurons turned off during fit time. It then continued to another Dense layer of 200 neurons followed by a dropout layer of 0.2 percent and one last hidden dense layer of 100 followed by 0.2 percent of dropouts. The output layer was a single dense neuron with a 'sigmoid' activation for class 0 and class 1. The model was compiled with a 'binary_crossentropy' loss function with custom Adam optimizer of learning_rate = 0.001. It monitored both 'accuracy' as well as area under the curve metric.

The deep neural network used batch size of 1000 instances, and initial epochs of 2000. This does not slow the training time because the model monitors validation data at runtime, and when the validation loss stops improving for 10 consecutive epochs, the training will stop automatically. Figure 1 illustrates the train/test loss versus number of epochs. It can be observed that initially both training loss and test loss decrease quickly. Test loss stops improving at around 81 epochs. The model patiently waited for another 10 epochs for test loss to decrease further and the training stopped after validation loss failed to decreased further. The final training loss for train and test are roughly the same when the model stopped, and no overfitting of the training set has been discovered based on the loss vs. Epochs curve. The find_best_prob was deployed to find the best cut off and average monetary loss. Details will be presented under Results section.

Ensemble - Model 6¶

The final model attempted used an ensemble of three models explored previously. Logistic Regression, Random Forest Classifier and XGBoost Classifier. Each model was initialized with the best parameter combination discovered during Grid search or Random search. The get_models method initializied a list of models to be used under our ultimate ensemble model and it returned a list of level-1 prediction models to be used. The fit_ensemble method trained each level-1 model in the models list and used cross_val_predict to obtain out of fold prediction probability for each training instance using the provided number of cross validation. The out of fold prediction probability of both class 0 and class 1 for all models in the models list are stacked together to be used as the predictor for level-2, which uses LogisticRegression to again be fitted with given labels. fit_ensemble returns the level-2 Logistic Regression classifier to be used for prediction. predict_ensemble takes in a list of trained models (level-1) and trained level-2 model as well as test data. It goes through each model from the level-1 models list to get the prediction probability for test data to be stacked, and then uses the stacked predictive probabilities for level-2 logistic regression model prediction. Finally, it returns the predictive probability for both classes as the ultimate result. The find_best_prob was deployed to find the best cut off and average monetary loss. Details will be presented under Results section.

3. Results¶

Table 1 shows a comparison of the six different models attempted. The test AUC for the models ranged from 0.766 to 0.991, and accuracy scores on the test data ranged from 0.71 to 0.97. The model with the worst overall performance was the Logistic Regression (Model 1) without additional interaction terms. While it was the second fastest to train (at 5 minutes, 30 seconds), its performance was poor. Logistic Regression with Interactions (Model 2) had improved performance when compared with the straightforward Logistic Regression model, but the training time was very long, at over five days. Random Forest (Model 3) showed improved performance over the two logistic models, with a training time of 1 hour, 17 minutes. The top three performing models were XGBoost, Neural Network, and Ensemble. Each produced a test AUC of over 0.98, with Neural Network (Model 5) producing a slightly better test AUC in the shortest overall training time (1 minutes, 56 seconds).

Recall for a class means among all the instances that are in that class, how many can the model predict to be that class. Of course, these are the metrics for a default decision cut-off. Because penalties for misclassifications were different for each class, further exploration of optimal cut-off values was necessary.

4. Conclusion¶

Six total predictive models were explored to find the best option for minimizing financial loss. The hyperparameters for each model were tuned, and the tuned models were then examined to find the optimal prediction cut-off given the penalties for false positives and false negatives. Ultimately, Neural Network Model 5 is recommended for minimizing financial loss. It provides the lowest estimated financial penalties on average, with the best combination of false positives and false negatives. Model 5 produced an average loss of $1.41 per instance. Although it was not a consideration in model recommendation, Model 5 also had the fastest training time, at 1 minutes 56 seconds.

To further improve predictions, future models could explore more comprehensive ensemble methods. If additional information regarding the data set is made available, more targeted feature engineering could also be incoporated.

        return float(re.sub(pattern, '', original ))

def get_acc_score(model, x, y):
    return model.score(x, y)
  
def plot_roc_curve_custom(x_test, y_test, model, nn_model = False, probability=False):
    if not nn_model:
        if probability:
            fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, model[:,1])
        else:
            fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1])
    else:
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict(x_test))
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', label='Randomized Search CV (AUC = ' + str(round(roc_auc, 5)) + ')')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.legend(loc='lower right')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic',fontdict={'fontsize':20},pad=15)
    plt.show()

def get_confusion_matrix(y, yhat,mat_title="Confusion Matrix"):
    x_axis_labels = ['0','1']
    y_axis_labels = ['0','1']
    cm_n = confusion_matrix(y, yhat)
    ax = sns.heatmap(cm_n,cmap='Blues',annot=True,fmt='2d',xticklabels=x_axis_labels, yticklabels=y_axis_labels)
    ax.set(xlabel='Predicted Label', ylabel='True Label')
    ax.set_title(mat_title,fontdict={'fontsize':20},pad=15)
    plt.show()
    
def get_classification_report(x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, pred, model, nn_model=False):
    """
    This function is used to get comprehensive classification report:
    Training Accuracy, Test Accuracy, print classification_report
    plot confusion matrix, and plot roc curve.
    """
    if not nn_model:
        print(f"Train accuracy: {get_acc_score(model, x_train, y_train):,.5f}")
    print("Test result:")
    print(f"Normalized Total Dollar Loss on Test Data {estimate_total_loss(y_test, pred):,.5f}\n")
    print(classification_report(y_test,pred))
    if not nn_model:
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(x_test)[:,1], pos_label=1)
    else:
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict(x_test), pos_label=1)
    print(f"Test AUC: {auc(fpr, tpr):,.5f}")
    plot_roc_curve_custom(x_test, y_test, model, nn_model=nn_model)
    if not nn_model:
        plot_confusion_matrix(model, x_test, y_test,colorbar=False)
        plt.grid(False)
    else:
        get_confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)

cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
verbose = 15

def cv_common(df, columns):
    cv_result_summary = df[columns]
    cv_result_summary.index  = np.arange(1,len(cv_result_summary)+1)
    cv_result_summary = cv_result_summary.reset_index()
    return cv_result_summary
    

def cv_summary(estimator, columns):
    df = pd.DataFrame(estimator.cv_results_)
    cv_result_summary = cv_common(df, columns)
    cv_result_summary = cv_result_summary.rename(columns = {
        "index": "param_combination",
        "mean_test_score": "mean_validation_score",
        "rank_test_score": "rank_validation_score"
    })
    return cv_result_summary

# Calculate Normalized Total Loss in Dollars
def estimate_total_loss(y_test, pred):
    """
    This function is used to calculate normalized total financial loss based on misclassification.
    """
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,pred)
    predict_0_wrong_d = cm[1,0]*25
    predict_1_wrong_d = cm[0,1]*100
    return (predict_1_wrong_d+predict_0_wrong_d)/np.sum(cm)

# Find best probability and cut off for given model
def find_best_prob(model, X_test, y_test, nn_model = False, probability=False):
    """
    This function use 0.005 increments to find best cut off among 0.01 to 0.5 probability range based
    on best_dollar_loss calculated using estimate_total_loss above.
    """
    best_dollar_loss = 100
    best_cut_off = 0.5
    for i in np.arange(0.5,1,0.005):
        if not nn_model:
            if probability:
                y_hat = (model[:,1] > i).astype('int32')
            else:
                y_hat = (model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]>i).astype("int32")
        else:
            y_hat = (model.predict(X_test)>i).astype("int32")
        if best_dollar_loss > estimate_total_loss(y_test, y_hat):
            best_dollar_loss = estimate_total_loss(y_test, y_hat)
            best_cut_off = i
    return best_cut_off, best_dollar_loss

def plot_early_stop_rounds(model_loss):
    plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.plot(model_loss['loss'],lw=2.5, label='train')
    plt.plot(model_loss['val_loss'],lw=2.5, label = 'test')
    plt.title('Train/Test Loss vs. Epochs',fontdict={'fontsize':20},pad=15)
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Build Sequential NN model using Tensorflow and Keras
model = Sequential()
model.add(InputLayer(input_shape=(76,)))
model.add(Dense(units=250,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(units=200,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(units=100,activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(units=1,activation='sigmoid'))

# Compile model
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
                  metrics=['accuracy', tf.keras.metrics.AUC()])

# Set early stopping variable
early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', patience=10)

In [109]:
# Code ideas borrowed from: https://machinelearningmastery.com/blending-ensemble-machine-learning-with-python/
# get a list of base models
def get_models():
    models = list()
    models.append(('lr', pipeline_m6_lr))
    models.append(('rf', pipeline_m6_rf))
    models.append(('xgb', pipeline_m6_xgb))
    return models

# fit the ensemble
def fit_ensemble(models, X_train, y_train, cv = 5):
    # fit all models on the training set and use cross validation predict
    # to get prediction score for ensemble
    meta_X = list()
    for name, model in models:
        # get cross validation score
        print("Current processing: ", name)
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        preds_prob = cross_val_predict(model, X_train, y_train, verbose=15, 
                                       cv = cv, method='predict_proba',n_jobs=-2)
        # store predictions as input for ensembling
        meta_X.append(preds_prob)
    # create 2d array from predictions, each set is an input feature
    meta_X = hstack(meta_X)
    # define 2nd level ensemble model
    level2_ensemble = LogisticRegression()
    # fit on predictions from base models
    level2_ensemble.fit(meta_X, y_train)
    return level2_ensemble

# make a prediction with the ensemble models
def predict_ensemble(models, level2_ensemble, X_test):
    # make predictions with base models
    meta_X = list()
    for name, model in models:
        # predict with base model
        yhat = model.predict_proba(X_test)
        # store prediction
        meta_X.append(yhat)
    # create 2d array from predictions, each set is an input feature
    meta_X = hstack(meta_X)
    # predict
    return level2_ensemble.predict_proba(meta_X)
